{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14592"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.14,0.17,0.47,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112801"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7285"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"4622"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112801"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after intentionally ingesting 20 tablets of propranolol 40 mg two hours ago. She has a history of performance anxiety for which she takes propranolol as required. On examination, she appears drowsy but rousable to voice. Her pulse rate is 42/min, blood pressure 85/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her ECG shows sinus bradycardia with first-degree heart block. She has already received activated charcoal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pairs of treatments is the most appropriate next step in managing this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isoprenaline and potassium chloride","Noradrenaline and calcium chloride","Adrenaline and high-dose insulin with glucose","Atropine and Intravenous fluids","Glucagon and sodium bicarbonate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with significant beta blocker toxicity characterised by bradycardia, hypotension, and drowsiness. Beta blocker overdose often requires multiple simultaneous interventions to support cardiac function and maintain perfusion, and is often a complex and multi-stage treatment process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the first instance, \u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine and Intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate. Atropine can transiently ameliorate bradycardia, while isotonic crystalloids\u2014such as Hartmann\u2019s solution or 0.9% sodium chloride\u2014may offer temporary improvement in hypotension. However, these interventions are usually only\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Etemporising. They frequently fail to fully reverse the profound hemodynamic instabilities resulting from the cardiotoxicity of beta-blockers,\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eespecially in severe overdoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline and high-dose insulin with glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be the ultimate step in managing this patient. Patients who require ongoing inotropic supports will usually need to transition to high dose insulin euglycemic therapy. Adrenaline provides immediate chronotropic and inotropic support through direct stimulation of beta receptors, helping to maintain cardiac output and blood pressure. High-dose insulin therapy (1 unit/kg bolus followed by infusion) with glucose supplementation has emerged as a crucial treatment due to its positive inotropic effects and ability to improve myocardial glucose utilisation in beta blocker toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon and sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E are not first-line treatments. While glucagon can increase heart rate and contractility through non-beta receptor mechanisms, its effects are often transient and less reliable than adrenaline. Sodium bicarbonate is not specifically indicated unless there is significant acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline and calcium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E would be less effective than adrenaline. Noradrenaline\u0027s alpha effects may worsen bradycardia, and calcium chloride offers no advantage over calcium gluconate in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoprenaline and potassium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. Isoprenaline may worsen hypotension due to vasodilation, and there is no indication for potassium supplementation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to the mechanism of action of the drug, significant propranolol overdoses may cause refractory bradycardia and hypotension due to ongoing beta-blockade. Severe cases may even require invasive measures such as extra-corporeal membranous oxygenation (ECMO) to maintain cardiac output.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta blocker overdose causes bradycardia, hypotension, and cardiogenic shock requiring multiple simultaneous therapies.","The use of high-dose insulin with glucose is an important consideration in treatment for beta blocker toxicity due to its positive inotropic effects. It is effective in massive beta blocker overdose and utilised in patients with ongoing haemodynamic instability despite other initial measures.","Adrenaline provides chronotropic and inotropic support in beta blocker toxicity while other therapies take effect."],"references":["Rotella JA, Greene SL, Koutsogiannis Z, Graudins A, Hung Leang Y, Kuan K, Baxter H, Bourke E, Wong A. Treatment for beta-blocker poisoning: a systematic review. Clin Toxicol (Phila). 2020 Oct;58(10):943-983. doi: 10.1080/15563650.2020.1752918. Epub 2020 Apr 20. PMID: 32310006. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32310006/","Lauterbach M. Clinical toxicology of beta-blocker overdose in adults. Basic Clin Pharmacol Toxicol. 2019; 125: 178\u2013186. https://doi.org/10.1111/bcpt.13231","Barrueto FJ Jr MD, MBA, FACHE. Beta-blocker poisoning. UpToDate [Internet]. UpToDate; last updated 4 September 2025. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/beta-blocker-poisoning"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14592"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-06T15:03:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T10:03:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7285"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112801"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"desc